inconsistent_txt: See folder 1-guidelines > non-checklists > document conflicts_record. Conflict is recorded here.  This journal has 2 different Guidlines:  Wiley: Would be marked Not Mentioned for all above criteria.  APS: As marked above

The journal's definition of "freely available" data does not necessarily mean "publicly available":  They consider data are freely available if data are provided by corresponding author on reasonable request (see data availability statement excerpts)

Complicated.  The guide to authors comes as word document (which I used) and you can download a 'version' from it as  PDF.  Also the word doc can send you to a similar (but not identical) Elsevier headed PDF which is not identical.  But there were no obvious inconsistencies for the things we ask about (I think!)

journal: journal of cerebral blood flow and metabolism

inconsistent_txt: JUST A COMMENT: author stuff refers to many guidelines listed at the start.  It mentions Prisma-P which was not listed by us.

All datasets on which the conclusions of the paper rely must be either deposited in publicly   available repositories...    For all journals, BioMed Central strongly encourages all datasets on which the conclusions of the manuscript rely to be either deposited in publicly available repositories     The recommendation for depositing data sets is inconsistent, some places it states you MUST do it and other places it uses language such as "encourages".

This paragraph is potentially ambivalent:  'Work published in the APS Journals must necessarily be independently verifiable. Authors describing results derived from unique materials, for example: antibodies, recombinant plasmids and cloned DNAs, and mutant cell lines or viruses, are expected to make such materials available to qualified investigators on request. In addition, authors are encouraged to make data that underlie the conclusions reported in the article freely available via public repositories or available to readers upon request.' [How can work be independently verifiable if the authors are only 'encouraged' to make data available?    NOTE it does mention the JAPPL/APS Curran Everett articles under 'Related Editorials and guidelines'  You also get there by clicking to the Rigor and Reproducibility Checklist.    This starts with the following entreaty: Articles published in APS journals must report experimental methods in sufficient detail to allow for transparency of data and replication by others. Authors are highly encouraged to use the Rigor and Reproducibility Checklist when preparing their original research submissions for APS Journals.
